that don't have "power". Is there anything that  

357
00:31:11,040 --> 00:31:15,120
you suggest these folks do differently or think 
about this differently or is it kind of the same  

358
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:20,400
thing? In the end everyone has power in some way. 
How would you think about this if you're just,  

359
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:25,920
say, a product manager, individual contributor?
I think one of the most important balances in  

360
00:31:25,920 --> 00:31:32,560
terms of the asking step is both asking clearly, 
but asking with great humility. And this actually  

361
00:31:32,560 --> 00:31:37,880
works whether you're in a position of power or 
not because I think a lot of folks will go so far  

362
00:31:37,880 --> 00:31:42,640
to the end of humility. They say, "Well, I'm not 
going to say this out loud at all." But in fact,  

363
00:31:42,640 --> 00:31:48,560
if you're willing to say, I really disagree with 
this product decision and I would really prefer  

364
00:31:48,560 --> 00:31:53,120
that we make this different decision. I know it's 
not my call and I'm just one opinion and a lot of  

365
00:31:53,120 --> 00:31:56,160
people are going to see things differently 
and that's fine, but it's important to me  

366
00:31:56,160 --> 00:32:00,920
that you know that. So what do you think? 
Are you willing to reconsider this?"
 

367
00:32:00,920 --> 00:32:09,280
That's such a great approach. It's very 
not scary to say that. It also, I think,  

368
00:32:09,280 --> 00:32:13,760
highlights something I wanted to touch on is I 
think people have a lot more influence and power  

369
00:32:13,760 --> 00:32:21,240
than they think they do. Say a PM on a team 
disagrees with a plan for a product. People  

370
00:32:21,240 --> 00:32:25,680
actually care about your opinion and you could 
actually change things. But just telling them,  

371
00:32:26,360 --> 00:32:30,480
"I think this is a bad idea." And you often 
don't. Is that what you find, that people  

372
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:34,640
have a lot more influence than they think they 
do? Anything along those lines that comes up?
 

373
00:32:34,640 --> 00:32:42,280
You're giving me deep goosebumps because I 
think this is a really underappreciated thing  

374
00:32:42,280 --> 00:32:47,440
in terms of asking for what we want because 
especially in the PM world, we're trained to  

375
00:32:47,440 --> 00:32:51,280
look for data. We're not just going to state an 
opinion. We're going to say, "Oh, the AB test  

376
00:32:51,280 --> 00:32:58,680
said this. Or 30% of our users do this, or the 
ROI on this is X." And data is great. We love  

377
00:32:58,680 --> 00:33:04,320
data for a reason of course. And I think people 
forget about exactly what you're highlighting,  

378
00:33:04,320 --> 00:33:09,840
that your relationships matter, and that just 
your opinion because you believe something or  

379
00:33:09,840 --> 00:33:15,080
because you want something often that's enough.
Because guess what? You're in a relationship with  

380
00:33:15,080 --> 00:33:21,120
these people you work with. They care about 
you. You have some sort of leverage with them.  

381
00:33:21,120 --> 00:33:25,880
And I think that often people go the other way 
and say, "Oh, I've got power. I'm going to try  

382
00:33:25,880 --> 00:33:29,400
and leverage it." But actually, if you go the 
other direction and you're humble and you say,  

383
00:33:29,400 --> 00:33:34,720
"I know I can't make you do anything, it's not 
my call to make. But man, this is really what  

384
00:33:34,720 --> 00:33:39,680
I want. I'm just going to put it out there and 
ask." That I think it feels really vulnerable  

385
00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:44,320
and uncomfortable to not lean on data as a sort of 
way of saying, "No, no, I'm right, so you should  

386
00:33:44,320 --> 00:33:47,920
believe what I believe." But just say, "Actually, 
I don't know that I'm right. This is just what I  

387
00:33:47,920 --> 00:33:52,000
think and I hope that's enough on its own."
Do you find that that's actually a crutch a lot  

388
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:55,760
of times to people not saying anything is they 
don't have that data? They don't have evidence  

389
00:33:55,760 --> 00:34:00,680
and they just, "I shouldn't say anything. If 
someone asks for why I don't have a great answer,  

390
00:34:00,680 --> 00:34:05,920
I just think this is what should be."
Totally. And I think there's a balance  

391
00:34:05,920 --> 00:34:11,360
there as with anything. Is ignoring data and 
going in gut all the time, great? Probably not,  

392
00:34:11,360 --> 00:34:20,560
right? We use data for a reason, but I think 
there are all these moments when we are making  

393
00:34:20,560 --> 00:34:26,960
a gut decision and having all the data there 
means having the opinion set out loud. I think  

394
00:34:26,960 --> 00:34:31,320
often the dangers of people saying, "Oh, I 
don't have data to back this up. It's just  

395
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:35,520
what I think. And I'm not sure people are going to 
agree with me, so I'm just not going to say it."
 

396
00:34:35,520 --> 00:34:39,560
So we don't have the data of all those gut 
opinions of these subject matter experts in  

397
00:34:39,560 --> 00:34:44,920
the room, even though that gut information to 
me is just as important as anything we could  

398
00:34:44,920 --> 00:34:50,720
get from the SQL database or whatever.
Before we move on to step three, you talked about  

399
00:34:50,720 --> 00:34:55,160
the opposite of asking for what you want. This was 
just step two is just complaining and being angry  

400
00:34:55,160 --> 00:34:59,360
later like, "I knew this project was going to 
fail. I knew this was a terrible deadline. I knew  

401
00:34:59,360 --> 00:35:05,360
this design was not great." Anything more you want 
to say along those lines of just like, "If you're  

402
00:35:05,360 --> 00:35:10,960
not asking for what you want, complaining is often 
a sign that you should be doing that more"?
 

403
00:35:10,960 --> 00:35:20,360
To me, complaints are great inspiration. 
To me, I love radical candor, for example,  

404
00:35:21,920 --> 00:35:25,640
where I try to go a step further than 
radical candor is to not just say, "Hey,  

405
00:35:25,640 --> 00:35:32,520
here's my feedback. Just wanted you to know." But 
to say, "And I want something. I would like to see  

406
00:35:32,520 --> 00:35:41,640
an outcome." And so I think that to me it's all 
about the effective framing that the complaint  

407
00:35:41,640 --> 00:35:44,920
is probably not going to be an effective way to 
do it, but it can be great inspiration to say,  

408
00:35:44,920 --> 00:35:49,400
"Gosh, that complaining means I'm frustrated. 
What am I frustrated about? Let me envision  

409
00:35:49,400 --> 00:35:53,320
that better future. Let me think about what's 
an effective way to actually move towards that.  

410
00:35:53,320 --> 00:35:58,880
What's an effective way to communicate that desire 
that's actually likely to get me towards a yes?"
 

411
00:35:58,880 --> 00:36:05,600
And so when we actually embrace that sort of 
frustration, annoying, complaining thing and  

412
00:36:05,600 --> 00:36:10,000
follow that thread down and think about how to be 
effective that way, we can actually get something  

413
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:15,000
really compelling and useful, but it requires 
actually embracing that part of ourselves that  

414
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:19,080
sometimes we're a little bit ashamed of like, 
"Oh, I don't like that whiny part of myself. I'm  

415
00:36:19,080 --> 00:36:24,320
just going to push that one down versus actually 
taking what it has to say as important data."
 

416
00:36:24,320 --> 00:36:29,120
That's a really good point. I think that's 
actually another blocker for a lot of people  

417
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:33,360
is just, "I don't want to be a complaining person. 
I just want to be like, let's do this. I'm in,  

418
00:36:33,360 --> 00:36:37,160
let's go. I don't want to be seen as a 
squeaky wheel." Is there anything you say  

419
00:36:37,160 --> 00:36:43,960
there about as a resistance point for people?
Well, I'm a big fan of internal family systems,  

420
00:36:43,960 --> 00:36:49,480
which is this sort of psychotherapy technique 
that really talks about parts and the sort of  

421
00:36:49,480 --> 00:36:53,760
parts of ourselves and the ways in which they 
don't always agree with each other. Part of why  

422
00:36:53,760 --> 00:36:58,440
I love this approach is, A, because we already use 
this language. We say, "Part of me thinks this,  

423
00:36:58,440 --> 00:37:03,720
a part of me thinks that." And really when I talk 
about how to work through resistance, really it's  

424
00:37:03,720 --> 00:37:09,240
about embracing and validating all of our parts.
Because often we're really comfortable with one  

425
00:37:09,240 --> 00:37:13,320
part of ourselves that we think is, "Oh, 
this part is virtuous and good and great,  

426
00:37:13,320 --> 00:37:19,280
and this part is whiny and bad, and not great, 
and I don't respect that part of me as much." So  

427
00:37:19,280 --> 00:37:25,120
really to sort of ask effectively, we generally 
need to embrace all these parts and really bring  

428
00:37:25,120 --> 00:37:30,600
in all the information they're bringing in because 
if we ignore the part that's really scared to ask,  

429
00:37:30,600 --> 00:37:34,440
well, then we're going to stay stuck.
Versus if we come in and say, "Hey, buddy,  

430
00:37:34,440 --> 00:37:39,720
why are you scared? You seem terrified. What's 
going on? Oh, well man, you think your whole  

431
00:37:39,720 --> 00:37:44,120
professional reputation has staked on this and 
you're an imposter and they're going to find out,  

432
00:37:44,120 --> 00:37:47,400
and then you'll never work again? Well, of 
course you'd be scared. That makes a ton of  

433
00:37:47,400 --> 00:37:52,240
sense." And by embracing that, instead of 
ignoring that and being ashamed of that,  

434
00:37:52,240 --> 00:37:56,720
that is often how we soften those fears and 
say, "I know that's scary, but we also know  

435
00:37:56,720 --> 00:38:01,520
that's not really true. You're not an imposter, 
right? You're an experienced professional."
 

436
00:38:01,520 --> 00:38:05,320
Man, there's so many threads we can't follow 
here. This whole line of internal family  

437
00:38:05,320 --> 00:38:06,280
systems, right?
Mm-hmm.
 

438
00:38:06,920 --> 00:38:11,480
That's its own podcast episode potentially. And 
then imposter syndrome, we've touched a bunch  

