00:39:06,840 --> 00:39:12,840
100% have told me that it's a transformative 
life experience for them. And you had a bonus  

451
00:39:12,840 --> 00:39:17,640
transformational piece. So anyway, if people want 
to check out that episode, I will include it in  

452
00:39:17,640 --> 00:39:21,960
the show notes. But the reason I brought it up is 
Carole shared this framework for how to actually  

453
00:39:21,960 --> 00:39:26,240
give feedback in a way where people can receive 
it that I'll just highlight here. I have it here.
 

454
00:39:26,240 --> 00:39:30,560
And it's somewhat related to nonviolent 
communication, which is what you touched on. And  

455
00:39:30,560 --> 00:39:36,200
she told me, actually, she taught this way before 
nonviolent communication came out with their whole  

456
00:39:36,200 --> 00:39:41,800
philosophy. And it's basically when you want 
to give someone feedback, the template is when  

457
00:39:41,800 --> 00:39:49,760
you do a behavior, I feel a feeling, and she's 
big on like say actual feeling word not like,  

458
00:39:49,760 --> 00:39:54,480
"I feel like, or I feel that," blah, blah, 
blah. And step three is, "I'm telling you this  

459
00:39:54,480 --> 00:40:01,360
because..." and then what you want them to change. 
Do you find that sort of approach helpful?
 

460
00:40:01,360 --> 00:40:05,760
I do. I teach the same thing. I 
think sort of Carole's approach  

461
00:40:05,760 --> 00:40:12,000
and nonviolent communication, DBT teaches 
a similar approach. They call dear man.
 

462
00:40:12,920 --> 00:40:16,400
To me, what's DBT?
It's a dialectical behavioral therapy.  

463
00:40:16,400 --> 00:40:23,280
It's related to CBT. So there's kind of rough 
consensus in the sort of personal development  

464
00:40:23,280 --> 00:40:31,160
world of how to ask. And really what they have in 
common is around staying really factual because I  

465
00:40:31,160 --> 00:40:36,120
think that what can we know factually well? We 
can know our thoughts, we can know our feelings  

466
00:40:36,120 --> 00:40:41,960
because no one else can know that better than 
us. Maybe we can trust our eyes. What would a  

467
00:40:41,960 --> 00:40:47,480
video camera have recorded? And that's about it.
So I think often we get really distracted by all  

468
00:40:47,480 --> 00:40:52,040
these stories we have about the data, but 
when we bring it back to that fundamental  

469
00:40:52,040 --> 00:40:56,160
core of this is what I think, this is what 
I feel, this is what I've observed in the  

470
00:40:56,160 --> 00:41:02,600
world, it tends to make the ask a lot clearer 
versus these stories like you mentioned of,  

471
00:41:02,600 --> 00:41:07,480
"I feel like you're an asshole." It's like, 
"Well, that's a story. That's not a fact."
 

472
00:41:07,480 --> 00:41:13,280
Yeah. I feel that is not the right way to say 
I feel. What do you actually feel? No. Okay,  

473
00:41:13,280 --> 00:41:17,000
so let's move to step three. We've been going 
on this whole tangent of therapy and stuff,  

474
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:21,400
which is amazing, but let's make sure we 
cover all three steps. So step one again  

475
00:41:21,400 --> 00:41:27,240
was articulate what you want. Step two is 
ask for what you want. What's step three?
 

476
00:41:28,040 --> 00:41:32,320
So to me step three is actually 
the trickiest for most people.
 

477
00:41:33,120 --> 00:41:36,400
So far, they're all tricky to me.
Oh yeah, they're all tricky, for sure.
 

478
00:41:36,400 --> 00:41:39,800
The most tricky.
But step three is accept  

479
00:41:39,800 --> 00:41:46,640
the response. And it might seem so simple, 
but it actually is kind of subtle. And so  

480
00:41:47,600 --> 00:41:53,840
one reason is that idea of sort of the whole 
body yes or the hell yes. Because I think often  

481
00:41:53,840 --> 00:41:59,640
we really want a yes. And so we're very, very 
biased to look for a yes versus accepting no,  

482
00:41:59,640 --> 00:42:04,280
"That was a no." If someone made this face, 
that's a no. It doesn't matter what comes out  

483
00:42:04,280 --> 00:42:14,800
of their mouth. And so the challenge of accepting 
the response is often that of hearing the no,  

484
00:42:14,800 --> 00:42:20,560
but not over accepting or under accepting it.
Because I think sometimes what people who are  

485
00:42:20,560 --> 00:42:24,120
really afraid to ask will do is they say, oh, 
well, that was a no. So it's no forever and  

486
00:42:24,120 --> 00:42:28,120
I should never ask again. My dream is dead 
and nothing is ever going to happen for me  

487
00:42:28,120 --> 00:42:34,120
again." And that's because they get so scared. 
But actually no, that's over accepting. The no  

488
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:39,640
is just from this person right now in the way that 
you asked, which doesn't necessarily mean anything  

489
00:42:39,640 --> 00:42:43,920
about the next time you ask to a different 
person in a different way, in a different time.
 

490
00:42:43,920 --> 00:42:49,960
And on the flip side, in that sort of more 
control freak mode, I think for them they'll  

491
00:42:49,960 --> 00:42:54,160
often skip over the response say, "Well, they 
said no, but they don't know what they're  

492
00:42:54,160 --> 00:42:59,960
talking about." Or they're my direct report, 
so they have to do what I say. So these are  

493
00:42:59,960 --> 00:43:07,360
all fundamentally disrespectful ways to operate in 
this relationship. When we're talking about asking  

494
00:43:07,360 --> 00:43:11,040
for what we want, we're talking about influence. 
So you need to have good relationships. You  

495
00:43:11,040 --> 00:43:17,040
can't be influential with a bad relationship.
So really accepting the response is about, yes,  

496
00:43:17,040 --> 00:43:21,880
I'm going to be genuine about what I want, but 
I'm also going to genuinely care about you and  

497
00:43:21,880 --> 00:43:28,720
have deep respect for your ability to consent 
or not consent to whatever the ask is. Because  

498
00:43:28,720 --> 00:43:33,920
I think the counterintuitive thing is that 
often when we really respect people's no's,  

499
00:43:35,080 --> 00:43:41,080
it can actually be more influential, more 
motivating. If someone says, "Okay. I'm not ready  

500
00:43:41,080 --> 00:43:46,680
to deliver this on time." Be like, "Okay. Well, 
I'm going to give the project to another person."
 

501
00:43:46,680 --> 00:43:51,040
I'm taking your no at face value. And they say, 
"Oh gosh, well, I didn't realize that was going  

502
00:43:51,040 --> 00:43:56,280
to be the consequence. Maybe I can get it 
done by that time." And so that way you're  

503
00:43:56,280 --> 00:43:59,720
not forcing them and you're not coercing them, 
right? You're just saying, "No, you said no? So  

504
00:43:59,720 --> 00:44:03,480
that your no is no, and I accept that."
So it feels like part of the skill here is  

505
00:44:03,480 --> 00:44:09,960
preparing, is knowing. Some people just say no and 
that's okay. That's part of the experience. Part  

506
00:44:09,960 --> 00:44:15,920
of it is if there's this not yet component... We 
had Mihika Kapoor on the podcast. She has a PM at  

507
00:44:15,920 --> 00:44:22,600
Figma and she had this really great approach to 
building new things within companies is just like  

508
00:44:22,600 --> 00:44:27,320
everything to her is not yet and no is a not yet. 
And the way you phrased it is it could just be the  

509
00:44:27,320 --> 00:44:31,640
way you asked. It could be, maybe they'll agree 
if you can figure out a better way to pitch the  

510
00:44:31,640 --> 00:44:36,440
thing. Is there anything more you can add there 
about just this idea of it's not no forever?
 

511
00:44:36,440 --> 00:44:43,720
Acceptance of the response is primarily an 
emotional regulation issue because once we  

512
00:44:43,720 --> 00:44:49,040
get our emotions intact, it's just, is it yes or 
is it no? And if it's no, which it probably is,  

513
00:44:49,040 --> 00:44:53,040
most of the time the world tells us no, then 
the question is, "All right, what can I learn  

514
00:44:53,040 --> 00:44:57,320
from this? What am I going to try next?" And 
so when we're able to emotionally regulate,  

515
00:44:57,320 --> 00:45:02,200
it's all very cut and dry, right? It's like, 
"Okay. Here's data to tell me what to try next."
 

516
00:45:02,200 --> 00:45:07,880
And so really, 99% of the challenge tends to 
be all the feelings that come up for us when  

517
00:45:07,880 --> 00:45:13,200
we hear no. Because We hate hearing no. It's 
so uncomfortable. And so part of the practice  

518
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:17,800
of getting good at asking for what we want is 
recognizing you're going to hear no all the time,  

519
00:45:17,800 --> 00:45:22,840
and that's completely normal and fine, and it 
doesn't need to be something so scary or awful.
 

520
00:45:22,840 --> 00:45:29,000
Easier said than done in real life. Is there an 
example of either a client of yours... I know  

