"I've been a founder. I've worked on iconic 
products. I know how to do this. I'm a pro.  

533
00:46:30,560 --> 00:46:36,160
I'm just going to go in and do the work."
So instead of getting really clear on what  

534
00:46:36,160 --> 00:46:41,440
does success look like here or what's your 
culture or what are your expectations of me,  

535
00:46:41,440 --> 00:46:47,640
I just went in and made my best guess and went 
for it. And lo and behold, turns out what I came  

536
00:46:47,640 --> 00:46:52,640
in with, that supreme overconfidence was not 
what they wanted at all. They'd kind of been  

537
00:46:52,640 --> 00:46:58,240
in the trenches reinventing from the game to 
Slack. They'd been through layoffs, really hard  

538
00:46:58,240 --> 00:47:02,440
times together. So they wanted someone to come 
in humble and to earn their trust of this kind  

539
00:47:02,440 --> 00:47:12,720
of core team that had been together for years.
I just didn't get any of that. I wasn't hearing  

540
00:47:12,720 --> 00:47:17,320
that feedback. I wasn't hearing those nos, 
and I wasn't articulating what I wanted.  

541
00:47:17,320 --> 00:47:21,720
What I wanted was really very basic. I just 
wanted to figure out how to do a good job,  

542
00:47:21,720 --> 00:47:25,920
and I wanted to have a good relationship with 
the CEO because I was working for him. And you  

543
00:47:25,920 --> 00:47:31,360
need to have a good relationship with your 
boss. But the problem was in the first firing  

544
00:47:31,360 --> 00:47:38,560
anyway was I had not articulated those goals.
And so I shouldn't have been surprised when six  

545
00:47:38,560 --> 00:47:44,720
weeks into my tenure at Slack, I came back from 
my backpacking trip with my bachelor buddies,  

546
00:47:44,720 --> 00:47:49,840
and I had an email in my inbox saying, "Hey, 
you're fired. It seems like it's not working out.  

547
00:47:49,840 --> 00:47:56,520
Let me know how you want to wrap it up." So as 
you can imagine, I freaked out. I loved this job,  

548
00:47:56,520 --> 00:48:03,520
I love this company, so I profusely apologized. 
I said, "I'll do whatever it takes. I'm so sorry.  

549
00:48:04,800 --> 00:48:09,960
I'm going to be committed to turn this around."
And so early stage startup turns out firing  

550
00:48:09,960 --> 00:48:16,480
doesn't always stick. Monday morning, I had my 
job back. But obviously things were not the same  

551
00:48:16,480 --> 00:48:23,560
as they'd been before because in the second era, 
what I wanted was sort of better articulated more  

552
00:48:23,560 --> 00:48:28,840
clear, but all of a sudden that fear that had been 
under the surface, that insecurity was now very,  

553
00:48:28,840 --> 00:48:34,480
very present every day because I was terrified 
of was I going to get fired? Was I going to not  

554
00:48:34,480 --> 00:48:41,600
make the most of this opportunity? And so I 
went fully into people pleaser mode. And so  

555
00:48:41,600 --> 00:48:46,440
that meant that even though what I desperately 
wanted was to have this good relationship was  

556
00:48:46,440 --> 00:48:52,160
to be successful, build a great product. 
I had a year of one-on-ones with the CEO.
 

557
00:48:52,160 --> 00:48:56,720
I never, never ever asked for what 
I wanted. I never said it out loud  

558
00:48:57,480 --> 00:49:03,400
because I was scared. I was scared of what the 
consequences were. I knew there were a hundred PMs  

559
00:49:03,400 --> 00:49:08,760
standing behind me ready to take my job if the CEO 
is ever a moment unhappy with me. I said, "No, I'm  

560
00:49:08,760 --> 00:49:14,320
not going to take the risk. I'm too scared of what 
the consequences might be." And so I held all that  

561
00:49:14,320 --> 00:49:19,760
fear and all those desires of, "I just want to do 
a great job. I want us to be awesome partners and  

562
00:49:19,760 --> 00:49:24,520
build this amazing industry changing product."
I never said any of that stuff out loud. I just  

563
00:49:24,520 --> 00:49:32,240
put my head down and I tried to obey. And so as 
you can imagine, this didn't work very well. I was  

564
00:49:32,240 --> 00:49:37,160
feeling horrible day to day. I was terrified 
of this guy I was working for. And so again,  

565
00:49:37,160 --> 00:49:41,800
I shouldn't have been surprised, but I was, when 
I got fired for the second time. It wasn't quite  

566
00:49:41,800 --> 00:49:46,480
firing. But this time I'd come back from my 
honeymoon and I had a phone call on Monday  

567
00:49:46,480 --> 00:49:51,000
that said, "Seems like product management is 
not working out for Slack. We're actually just  

568
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:56,200
going to get rid of product. You're going to 
be user research. It's going to be fine."
 

569
00:49:56,200 --> 00:50:01,040
And for me, I love user research, but that was 
the beginning of my career. I was not interested  

570
00:50:01,040 --> 00:50:05,960
in going back to that. What was fascinating 
was at that point, I was actually able to  

571
00:50:05,960 --> 00:50:10,440
articulate what I wanted there and was willing 
to say it out loud. Because what I wanted was,  

572
00:50:10,440 --> 00:50:15,480
"No, let's keep me in product. I've got an idea 
for how we can run it." So I wrote a proposal,  

573
00:50:15,480 --> 00:50:19,640
I sent it around to the management team. Turns 
out, when you actually ask for what you want  

574
00:50:19,640 --> 00:50:25,400
out loud, you're much more likely to get it.
And so within a week, this new plan had traction  

575
00:50:25,400 --> 00:50:32,400
with the management team team and I had my old 
job back again. Everything was fine except of  

576
00:50:32,400 --> 00:50:39,000
course it wasn't fine because now I was scared, 
but the stakes seemed really high, and this is  

577
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:44,160
where that deep imposter syndrome sit in. I was 
like, "Am I even any good at this? Should I even  

578
00:50:44,160 --> 00:50:47,960
be in product management? Am I ever going to 
work in this industry again? Is this going  

579
00:50:47,960 --> 00:50:53,480
to be my dark secret that I take to the grave 
that Stewart Butterfield fired me three times?"
 

580
00:50:58,640 --> 00:51:04,120
I think what I couldn't be with in that moment 
was the no's, because I was getting no after no  

581
00:51:04,120 --> 00:51:10,080
after no after no from Stewart and the rest of 
the management team saying, "What you're doing  

582
00:51:10,080 --> 00:51:14,160
is not working for us, right? Your ask are not 
landing. You're not being effective in the way  

583
00:51:14,160 --> 00:51:19,320
that you want to be effective." And because I 
wasn't able to hear those no's again, because to  

584
00:51:19,320 --> 00:51:24,200
that emotional regulation standpoint, I 
couldn't handle the feelings of like, "Ugh,  

585
00:51:24,200 --> 00:51:28,280
maybe what I'm doing is not good enough."
So instead of pointing the finger at myself,  

586
00:51:28,280 --> 00:51:33,040
I pointed the finger at him. I said, "You know 
what? Actually this guy, he's not such a great  

587
00:51:33,040 --> 00:51:36,600
manager. He's not so good at product. I'm the 
one who was on the ground with the users. I  

588
00:51:36,600 --> 00:51:41,960
know what's right." Against all evidence to 
the contrary, by the way, is this product  

589
00:51:41,960 --> 00:51:48,960
luminary, visionary, famous person.
So clearly not based on any facts,  

590
00:51:48,960 --> 00:51:54,360
but it was an emotional issue of I couldn't 
deal with the reality of what I was doing was  

591
00:51:54,360 --> 00:52:00,360
not working. And so again, because I was not 
articulating what I wanted, I was not asking  

592
00:52:00,360 --> 00:52:04,600
for it and I certainly was not listening to 
the no's. I shouldn't have been surprised  

593
00:52:04,600 --> 00:52:09,480
when finally the third time it came down, and 
this time it was serious because we had HR.
 

594
00:52:09,480 --> 00:52:15,720
So it turns out once you hire HR, the firings 
are final. And so I only made it to a year at  

595
00:52:15,720 --> 00:52:22,240
Slack and it was a year of just utter torture 
because I spent that year being fully out of  

596
00:52:22,240 --> 00:52:27,400
integrity with myself. Never saying what I 
really wanted, how I really felt because it  

597
00:52:27,400 --> 00:52:33,640
didn't feel safe. I was too scared. I kept it 
all inside. And it took me six months or a year  

598
00:52:33,640 --> 00:52:39,480
even after that to really feel safe and okay 
again. It was a serious decompression time.
 

599
00:52:39,480 --> 00:52:47,440
My wife and I had a baby during that time. I was 
on zero sleep. It was a rough, rough period. But  

600
00:52:47,440 --> 00:52:52,960
the irony is that when I actually came out of 
that experience, the reality of it was extremely  

601
00:52:52,960 --> 00:52:57,400
simple. I hadn't articulated what I wanted. 
I hadn't asked for what I wanted. I had not  

602
00:52:57,400 --> 00:53:05,040
listened to the no's in response to my non-ask.
And so of course I was unhappy with the result.  

603
00:53:05,040 --> 00:53:08,440
Why would I have expected anything 
different? I wasn't the victim. Stewart  

604
00:53:08,440 --> 00:53:16,040
wasn't the villain. It was just ineffective 
asking. And so to me, especially because I  

605
00:53:16,040 --> 00:53:21,920
was already on that path towards coaching, 
that lesson hit really hard in terms of how  

606
00:53:21,920 --> 00:53:26,600
do we make this work more sustainable?
We stay in integrity with ourselves even  

607
00:53:26,600 --> 00:53:30,880
when it's hard, even when it's scary, even when 
we don't know exactly what the outcome is going  

608
00:53:30,880 --> 00:53:36,360
to be. And so that's really the story of how I 
became a coach, of seeing exactly how much I'd  

609
00:53:36,360 --> 00:53:40,400
screwed up at Slack and seeing how much I had 
suffered and how much a lot of people suffer  

610
00:53:40,400 --> 00:53:45,480
in these similar circumstances. All you have to 
do to turn it around is ask for what you want.
 

611
00:53:45,480 --> 00:53:52,360
So this is why I'm so passionate about this 
stuff because it can sound so fluffy to say,  

612
00:53:52,360 --> 00:54:00,160
"Oh, focus on integrity. Honor your desires. 
No, it's real life stuff of a year of suffering,  

613
00:54:00,160 --> 00:54:05,480
of pain, of fear." I don't want other people 
to be going through that and that's why I'm  

614
00:54:05,480 --> 00:54:11,560
so passionate about this stuff.
Wow, what a story. I love that it's  

615
00:54:11,560 --> 00:54:15,640
kind of a microcosm of everything we've talked 
about. You've did all the things that you teach  

616
00:54:15,640 --> 00:54:19,160
people to avoid.
Exactly.
 

617
00:54:19,160 --> 00:54:22,480
And I think what's interesting is you went 
through these three phases. Interestingly,  

618
00:54:22,480 --> 00:54:26,680
at the beginning, your first phase was you 
were not hearing the no's, but it was rooted  

619
00:54:26,680 --> 00:54:30,640
in this confidence that you're a founder, you're 
awesome. They're so lucky to have you. I know what  

620
00:54:30,640 --> 00:54:35,200
I'm doing, get out of my way. And then the third 
phase, you also, the issue there was you weren't  

621
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:41,080
hearing the no's, but it was more from fear of 
being fired again. And so it's interesting that  

622
00:54:41,080 --> 00:54:46,320
there's these different reasons you're not 
hearing what people are actually saying.
 

623
00:54:46,320 --> 00:54:51,560
Totally. Well, and to me, the first one is about 
articulation as well because I think that if  

624
00:54:51,560 --> 00:54:56,040
in the beginning it articulated that, "Yeah, I'm 
confident, but actually I want to do a really good  

625
00:54:56,040 --> 00:55:00,800
job and I want to have good relationships. 
So let me think about intentionally,  

626
00:55:00,800 --> 00:55:05,920
how do I create those outcomes?" But because 
I hadn't articulated that's what I wanted,  

627
00:55:05,920 --> 00:55:10,160
it didn't even occur to me like, "Oh yeah, I need 
to do some intentional relationship building,  

628
00:55:10,160 --> 00:55:13,880
figure out some metrics for success."
It was an early stage startup. There  

629
00:55:13,880 --> 00:55:19,400
wasn't a ton of sort of process or structure in 
place, suffice to say. And so if I wanted that,  

630
00:55:19,400 --> 00:55:24,160
I needed to create it myself, but because I hadn't 
articulated that any of that was important to me,  

631
00:55:24,160 --> 00:55:29,120
I just flew by the seat of my pants and it took 
failing to get some data to say, "Ooh, yeah,  

632
00:55:29,120 --> 00:55:34,080
maybe I need to look at this more closely."
I imagine you've gone through this exercise many  

633
00:55:34,080 --> 00:55:38,800
times, but say you were to do it again, what would 
you do differently and what do you think would've  

634
00:55:38,800 --> 00:55:42,720
happened? Do you think you would've stayed there 
for many, many years, had a product at Slack at  

635
00:55:42,720 --> 00:55:46,200
this point? Just imagining that reality, what 
would you have done differently? And then what  

636
00:55:46,200 --> 00:55:51,240
would you have imagined have turned out?
Well, I mean obviously broadly, I would've  

637
00:55:51,240 --> 00:55:56,480
asked for what I wanted and what I wanted was I 
wanted to do the best work of our life. I wanted  

638
00:55:56,480 --> 00:56:02,680
to have a deep professional partner in the CEO and 
the rest of the product and management team. And I  

639
00:56:02,680 --> 00:56:07,640
wanted to produce great work that people loved. 
And that was part of why I was attracted to the  

640
00:56:07,640 --> 00:56:12,000
culture and the mission and the company. 
And so this is what's tricky is of course,  

641
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:16,280
that's what I would've done. Now, do I 
know what the outcome would've been?
 

642
00:56:16,280 --> 00:56:21,360
No, I might've been fired even sooner. They 
might've said, "No, this is not working out.  

643
00:56:22,280 --> 00:56:26,920
Let's just be done here." So that's what's 
tricky about this is it really isn't about  

644
00:56:26,920 --> 00:56:32,800
the outcome. Of course, asking for what you want 
makes you more likely to get the outcome you want,  

645
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:39,440
but you don't do it for guarantee of a certain 
outcome because no one can promise you that. You  

646
00:56:39,440 --> 00:56:43,000
do it so you can stay in integrity with yourself 
and not suffer through all this. Because at  

647
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:47,480
least then I would've said, "You know what? It 
didn't work out. At least I'm not sitting here  

648
00:56:47,480 --> 00:56:52,040
suffering. I can get another job at another 
startup. It's not the end of the world."
 

649
00:56:52,040 --> 00:56:57,000
And I think that the mistake we make is pretending 
that it is of saying, going into fight or flight  

650
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:02,360
and saying, "This is a severe existential 
threat to who I am and my safety in the  

651
00:57:02,360 --> 00:57:07,440
world," versus being like, "I'm disappointed. 
I wish it had worked out, but it didn't."
 

652
00:57:07,440 --> 00:57:14,600
That's a really profound point that this practice 
isn't necessarily to just have everything work out  

653
00:57:14,600 --> 00:57:19,880
beautifully and to get the things you're looking 
for. It's to feel like you did, which you could  

654
00:57:19,880 --> 00:57:26,440
have and to feel integrity with yourself that you 
did what you needed to do and you're not going to  

655
00:57:26,440 --> 00:57:30,920
regret something down the road.
Indeed.
 

656
00:57:30,920 --> 00:57:36,040
I'm going to take a quick tangent down the being 
the first PM route real quick. There's a lot of  

657
00:57:36,040 --> 00:57:41,520
people that think about being the first PM at 
a startup join as the first PM. I imagine you  

658
00:57:41,520 --> 00:57:46,400
work with people asking for advice along these 
lines. It's classically a very challenging role.  

659
00:57:46,400 --> 00:57:50,760
Many people don't last. Many people follow your 
trajectory where it's like, "Oh, shit. What have  

660
00:57:50,760 --> 00:57:57,760
I done?" Any advice for people that are a first 
PM at a company or startup or thinking about  

661
00:57:57,760 --> 00:58:05,840
that role?" What can you tell them to help 
them be successful or at least not suffer?
 

662
00:58:05,840 --> 00:58:13,560
To me, it really is about the relationship with 
the CEO or with the founders because that's the  

663
00:58:13,560 --> 00:58:19,200
root of a lot of the issues that come out of that 
scenario because it's not always you. In my story,  

664
00:58:19,200 --> 00:58:23,360
I think it was primarily about me, but I also 
work with a lot of founders who are going  

665
00:58:23,360 --> 00:58:30,200
through really tough things. My clue to people who 
report to a founder is to say, "Imagine if you're  

666
00:58:30,200 --> 00:58:35,680
confused about how your founder is behaving. 
Imagine that they're terrified all the time,  

667
00:58:35,680 --> 00:58:40,680
and see if that makes their behavior more clear."
Because it is scary to be a founder. Everything  

668
00:58:40,680 --> 00:58:44,640
is on your shoulders. And I think a lot of 
people do feel that sense of high stakes all  

669
00:58:44,640 --> 00:58:51,560
the time. And so I think being real about 
that of what is the state that the person  

670
00:58:51,560 --> 00:58:57,600
or the people you're working for are in and sort 
of working within that versus sort of pretending  

671
00:58:57,600 --> 00:59:01,760
that it's something else or wishing that it were 
something else is the path to having a healthy  

672
00:59:01,760 --> 00:59:05,040
relationship. Because if you don't have a healthy 
relationship with the person you're working for,  

673
00:59:05,040 --> 00:59:10,080
you're not going to get anything done. You're 
not going to succeed in any meaningful way.
 

674
00:59:10,080 --> 00:59:15,760
I love that framework of how to think about why a 
founder is behaving in a certain way. Just maybe a  

675
00:59:15,760 --> 00:59:21,320
last following thread there is just what should 
people look for to help them understand if the  

676
00:59:21,320 --> 00:59:25,320
founder and them are a good fit, if they're going 
to have a good time working with that founder? Is  

677
00:59:25,320 --> 00:59:29,320
there anything just like questions they might ask 
or ways of operating that are useful to understand  

678
00:59:29,320 --> 00:59:34,680
like, "Okay, I think I'll be okay with this 
founder in this company as the first PM or not.
 

679
00:59:34,680 --> 00:59:40,320
I think it's a hard thing to generalize about, 
but to me it really is about understanding  

680
00:59:40,320 --> 00:59:47,720
expectations. I guess this is a predictable coming 
from me, "But what do you really want? Because I  

681
00:59:47,720 --> 00:59:52,320
think that often the founders put together a job 
description, but then they're faced with a real  

682
00:59:52,320 --> 00:59:57,120
human being who has real human subtleties and 
things they're good at or not so good at." And  

683
00:59:57,120 --> 01:00:02,800
so being very, very clear about expectations 
and of figuring out collaboratively a way to  

684
01:00:02,800 --> 01:00:10,400
work together that's effective to me is there's 
no guarantees of course, but it gives you a more  

685
01:00:10,400 --> 01:00:15,320
sure path to having a productive relationship.
It's actually something that I recommend to a lot  

686
01:00:15,320 --> 01:00:22,120
of founders for maybe their first 10 or 15, 
or 20 employees of just have a relationship  

687
01:00:22,120 --> 01:00:26,120
design conversation with each of them when 
they're first hired. Because I think a lot  

688
01:00:26,120 --> 01:00:30,600
of us come in naive the way I did, assuming, "Oh 
yeah, I'm just going to come in and do my thing  

689
01:00:30,600 --> 01:00:34,080
the way I've always done it. It's going 
to be fine." Versus coming in and saying,  

690
01:00:34,080 --> 01:00:39,080
"I actually don't know how I'm going to operate at 
this company. I have range like anyone has range,  

691
01:00:39,080 --> 01:00:43,640
and I don't know what this company needs and who 
else is here and sort of what my role and what  

692
01:00:43,640 --> 01:00:48,560
my place is going to be within these other 
people. And so by really understanding that  

693
01:00:48,560 --> 01:00:53,520
intentionally and not from a place of performance 
management, you're already doing this poorly,  

694
01:00:53,520 --> 01:00:58,160
you're in big trouble. But what is the best way 
to work together given who we have now and what  

695
01:00:58,160 --> 01:01:04,240
we want and what we need? Let's figure it out.
Coming back to our core topic, is there anything  

696
01:01:04,240 --> 01:01:08,280
that we didn't cover, anything that I 
should have asked you about the skill,  

697
01:01:08,280 --> 01:01:12,440
the art of asking for what you want? Anything 
else you want to leave listeners with?
 

698
01:01:12,440 --> 01:01:16,360
I do want to mention something that I hear a 
lot from founders when I talk about the piece  

699
01:01:16,360 --> 01:01:22,040
of working through resistance because I think 
a lot of them say, "Oh, you want me to let go  

700
01:01:22,600 --> 01:01:27,480
of fear and focus on what I want? Well, I 
mean, I've been running from fear my whole  

701
01:01:27,480 --> 01:01:33,200
career. That's how I'm so hard-working and I'm so 
smart is I'm always afraid I'm not good enough."
 

702
01:01:34,760 --> 01:01:41,640
Am I going to be able to do this job without 
fear hounding me every step of the way? I just  

703
01:01:41,640 --> 01:01:47,480
remember the first time I heard this, it broke 
my heart, and now I've heard it dozens of times  

704
01:01:47,480 --> 01:01:52,000
I'd say. So I mean, it really is. I think 
it's a belief that sits deep in the hearts  

705
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:58,920
of a lot of us high achieving Silicon Valley 
tech types of, "My fear of not being good  

706
01:01:58,920 --> 01:02:03,320
enough is what drives me to be great."
And I just want to come out here and say  

707
01:02:03,320 --> 01:02:10,320
there's other ways to motivate. You can motivate 
based on joy, based on vision, based on your  

708
01:02:10,320 --> 01:02:15,400
inspiration in this vision of what you want. 
I think a lot of folks I talk to are skeptical  

709
01:02:15,400 --> 01:02:19,440
understandably because operated a different 
